Non debuerat Postgatius recipere Palmeri coniecturam (CR. II, p. 39): rapinis pro ruinis. Ipse Palmer suam coniecturam hisce verbis commendat: „Ruinis is unsound for two reasons. First, Propertius is not inquiring into the cause oi the bankruptcies of men: secondly, ru inis could not, barley, by itself mean bankruptcies. Cicero’s ruinas fortunarum tuarum does not defend it”. Sed neutra causa gravis; noster enim hexameter spectat ad pentametrum praecedentem: „cur opes exhauriantur, quaeris3 luxuria, cui nimis indulgent muliereS, causa est fortu- narum illarum perditarum”. In hoc autem contextu ruinis, etiamsi non additur fortunarum vel tale quid, per se intelli- gitur.
